 How POKEY keyboard scanning works (from schematic + VHDL + SpinalHDL)

 POKEY has an internal 6-bit counter (bincnt, 0-63) cycling at ~15 kHz.
 - KEYBOARD_SCAN = ~bincnt (inverted) goes to external matrix
 - KEYBOARD_RESPONSE[0] (KR1) = main key return, active low (0 = key pressed)
 - KEYBOARD_RESPONSE[1] (KR2) = modifier return, active low

 POKEY checks modifiers via KR2 using keyboard_scan[5:4] (top 2 bits):
 - scan[5:4]="11" → Control (bincnt 0x00-0x0F range)
 - scan[5:4]="10" → Shift (bincnt 0x10-0x1F range)
 - scan[5:4]="00" → Break (bincnt 0x30-0x3F range)

 VHDL reference (ps2_to_atari800.vhdl): maintains 512-bit PS2 key bitmap →
 64-bit Atari bitmap → atari_keyboard(~keyboard_scan) → response(0). Modifiers
 checked on keyboard_scan(5:4) only. Console keys (Start/Select/Option) are
 separate outputs from PS2 F-key mappings.

 Our simplification: JOP does USB HID → Atari scan code translation in software.
 Hardware only needs: one active key + modifier flags → matrix response.
 POKEY only detects one key at a time anyway (single-key scanner with debounce).

 Step 1: Update AtariCtrl — keyboard injection + console keys

 File: atari/src/main/scala/atari800/AtariCtrl.scala

 Keyboard injection (replaces single keyboardResponse register)

 Add keyboardScan input (6 bits, from Atari POKEY via top-level).

 New register 0xC — keyboard state (JOP writes when key state changes):
 - [5:0] = Atari scan code (0-63, the bincnt value for this key)
 - [8]   = key pressed (1 = down, 0 = up)
 - [9]   = shift held
 - [10]  = control held
 - [11]  = break pressed
 - Default: 0x000 (no key, no modifiers)

 Hardware response logic (combinational, matching VHDL pattern):
 val keyResponse = B"11"  // default: nothing pressed

 // KR1: main key — compare ~keyboardScan with stored scanCode
 when(keyReg.pressed && (~io.keyboardScan).asUInt === keyReg.scanCode) {
   keyResponse(0) := False
 }
 // KR2: modifiers — check keyboard_scan[5:4] (matches VHDL lines 261-271)
 when(keyReg.breakKey && io.keyboardScan(5 downto 4) === B"00") {
   keyResponse(1) := False
 }
 when(keyReg.shift && io.keyboardScan(5 downto 4) === B"10") {
   keyResponse(1) := False
 }
 when(keyReg.control && io.keyboardScan(5 downto 4) === B"11") {
   keyResponse(1) := False
 }

 JOP-side translation is a simple lookup table: USB HID scancode → Atari 6-bit scan code.
 Shift/control/break come from the USB HID modifier byte. One register write per key event.

